	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Poultry farmers in Ghana express concerns over imports and impact of IEPA commitments</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 June 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Following a meeting with poultry farmers’ leaders concerned about the market impact of imported products, Ghanaian Vice-President John Dramani Mahama agreed that the government would sit down ‘with all the stakeholders in the poultry industry to find out the challenges and craft out possible solutions that will promote their activities and protect the industry in the coming years’. The Ghanaian government has already amended regulations ‘to allow poultry farmers to benefit from the Enterprise Development and Investment Fund’.</p><p>A spokesperson for Ghanaian poultry farmers meanwhile appealed to the government to implement the ECOWAS tariff laws, ‘which would discourage the importation of “cheaper” chicken’, which has consistently threatened the local poultry industry. ECOWAS adopted a common external tariff in 2005 for final consumer goods, including a tariff of 20% applicable to poultry. However a number of ECOWAS members apply additional trade measures in the poultry sector, notably Nigeria and Senegal, which both have a ban in place on imports of poultry products (introduced in 2002 and 2006 respectively).</p><p>The situation also needs to be seen against the background of 43% expansion in EU poultry meat exports to Ghana reported in the EC’s review of the agricultural situation in the EU in 2010. This rate of expansion of EU exports was almost twice the rate of expansion of total EU poultry meat exports.</p><p>Poultry exports to Ghana are however dwarfed by EU poultry exports to Benin, where according to World Bank estimates ‘90 percent of Benin’s poultry imports are informally re-exported to Nigeria’.</p><p>Meanwhile, an outbreak of Newcastle disease in poultry in Greater Accra, attributed to ‘mismanagement’, has been notified to the World Organisation for Animal Health.</p><p><b>Trends in EU poultry exports to Ghana and Benin and globally </b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
