<p>Source: Presentation to the Single CMO Management Committee, ‘The European eggs and poultry sector’, 17 February 2011&nbsp;</p><p>The EU poultry meat export trade was raised at the World Social Forum meeting in Dakar in February 2011, where Cameroonian analysts once again expressed concerns about the possible impact of an EPA on the poultry sector in Cameroon, specifically the limitations that the agreement would place on the use of trade-policy tools to protect the poultry sector. In 2006, the Cameroon government increased duties on imports of poultry meat to facilitate the recovery in a sector which had earlier been undermined by high volumes of imports of cheap, low-quality poultry-meat cuts. The concern is that the current trade-policy commitments included in Cameroon’s interim EPA will lead to an early phasing out of these protective measures, despite the continued vulnerability of the sector.</p><p>Press reports have sought to link the trade in EU poultry parts to EU agricultural support programmes, which it is maintained undercut local poultry producers.</p>
		
		
