				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The 43% increase in EU exports of poultry-meat products to Ghana in 2010 broadly mirrored the 45% increase in EU poultry-meat exports to the ACP as a whole in 2010. This trade however is not driven by export refunds, which are almost exclusively paid on frozen whole-bird exports to Middle-Eastern markets (the ACP trade consists of frozen poultry cuts). Nor is it driven by EU coupled poultry-sector-specific payments or even payments under the single payment scheme (since no such assistance is extended to the EU poultry sector). The principal market management tool used in the EU is a system of high import tariffs backed up by a special safeguard clause.</p><p>As a 2005 EC evaluation of the poultry regime pointed out, the trade with ACP countries is ‘primarily driven by the need to dispose of unwanted cuts, for which demand is very low on the EU internal market’. This trade will continue, ‘provided that the export price (less transport costs) [is] greater than the costs of disposal’.</p><p>This makes government trade policy in the poultry sector critical. This is particularly the case in West Africa, where analysis suggests that West African producers do not have a comparative advantage in the global poultry trade. However, as the illicit trade between Benin and Nigeria highlights, this requires concerted policy action at the regional level if it is not to lead to extensive cross-border smuggling which undermines domestic markets and national policy. In the case of Benin, the alleged level of smuggling is equivalent to one-eighth of Nigerian domestic consumption of poultry meat and more than the entire national consumption of poultry meat of Benin in 2008.</p><p>Setting in place a common and harmonised trade regime for poultry meat in West and Central Africa would for these reasons appear essential for the future development of the sector.</p>
		</div>
		
